15
00:00:37,550 --> 00:00:41,000
The expected value
of a random variable

16
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:42,637
comes up in all sorts
of applications.

17
00:00:42,637 --> 00:00:44,720
We're going to spend a
whole week talking about it

18
00:00:44,720 --> 00:00:46,980
and some of next week
talking about variations

19
00:00:46,980 --> 00:00:48,496
from the expected value.

20
00:00:48,496 --> 00:00:49,870
And it's probably
one of the best

21
00:00:49,870 --> 00:00:52,190
tools you have for
working with probability

22
00:00:52,190 --> 00:00:54,289
problems in practice.

23
00:00:54,289 --> 00:00:55,747
So let's write down
the definition.

24
00:00:55,747 --> 00:01:04,129


25
00:01:04,129 --> 00:01:12,320
The expected value
also has other names.

26
00:01:12,320 --> 00:01:23,570
It's also known as the
average or the mean

27
00:01:23,570 --> 00:01:24,683
of a random variable.

28
00:01:24,683 --> 00:01:29,390


29
00:01:29,390 --> 00:01:41,950
Random variable R over
a probability space S

30
00:01:41,950 --> 00:01:44,520
is denoted by a lot of ways.

31
00:01:44,520 --> 00:01:48,760
We're going to use Ex
to denote it, Ex of R.

32
00:01:48,760 --> 00:01:52,070
And it's the sum over all
possible outcomes in the sample

33
00:01:52,070 --> 00:01:55,670
space of the value of
the random variable

34
00:01:55,670 --> 00:02:01,190
on that outcome times the
probability of that outcome.

35
00:02:01,190 --> 00:02:04,310
In other words, the expected
value of a random variable

36
00:02:04,310 --> 00:02:09,080
is just a weighted average
of all possible values

37
00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:13,380
of the random variable where
the weight is the probability

38
00:02:13,380 --> 00:02:15,910
of that happening.

39
00:02:15,910 --> 00:02:27,438
For example, suppose we
roll a fair six sided die.

40
00:02:27,438 --> 00:02:30,860


41
00:02:30,860 --> 00:02:33,810
So the numbers that
come up are 1 to 6.

42
00:02:33,810 --> 00:02:37,890
And we let R be the
random variable denoting

43
00:02:37,890 --> 00:02:40,135
the outcome, 1 through 6.

44
00:02:40,135 --> 00:02:43,330


45
00:02:43,330 --> 00:02:45,990
So the expected
value of the role,

46
00:02:45,990 --> 00:02:50,160
we can easily compute
from the definition.

47
00:02:50,160 --> 00:02:54,890
Well, there's a 1/6 chance
that it comes out a 1.

48
00:02:54,890 --> 00:02:56,200
The next outcome would be a 2.

49
00:02:56,200 --> 00:02:59,600
That happens with 1/6 chance.

50
00:02:59,600 --> 00:03:03,025
3, 4, 5, and six all
happen with a 1/6 chance.

51
00:03:03,025 --> 00:03:06,680


52
00:03:06,680 --> 00:03:13,000
If I sum up 1, 2, 3, 4 up to
6, I get 6 times 7 over 2 times

53
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:16,910
the 1/6 is just 7
over 2 or 3 and 1/2.

54
00:03:16,910 --> 00:03:19,590


55
00:03:19,590 --> 00:03:23,320
So expected value when I roll
a die, a fair six sided die,

56
00:03:23,320 --> 00:03:25,320
is just 3 and 1/2.

57
00:03:25,320 --> 00:03:27,880
And as you can see
from this example,

58
00:03:27,880 --> 00:03:31,210
the expected value doesn't
have to be attainable by one

59
00:03:31,210 --> 00:03:33,030
of the outcomes.

60
00:03:33,030 --> 00:03:36,730
You don't get a 3 and
1/2 when you roll a die.

61
00:03:36,730 --> 00:03:39,840
But that's the average value.

62
00:03:39,840 --> 00:03:44,080
Now the expected value, the
expectation, the average,

63
00:03:44,080 --> 00:03:46,812
the mean, they're
all the same thing.

64
00:03:46,812 --> 00:03:48,770
They're all defined based
on a random variable.

65
00:03:48,770 --> 00:03:50,890
They all mean the same thing.

66
00:03:50,890 --> 00:03:54,384
They are all different
than the median.

67
00:03:54,384 --> 00:03:55,800
That's something
that's different.

68
00:03:55,800 --> 00:03:58,400
So let me define the median.

69
00:03:58,400 --> 00:04:02,090
Basically it is the
outcome which splits

70
00:04:02,090 --> 00:04:03,390
the probabilities in half.

71
00:04:03,390 --> 00:04:05,030
In other words, you've
got a 50% chance

72
00:04:05,030 --> 00:04:08,260
of being bigger than the median
and a 50% chance of being

73
00:04:08,260 --> 00:04:09,760
smaller.

74
00:04:09,760 --> 00:04:17,209
Now precisely you can
define it this way.

75
00:04:17,209 --> 00:04:24,950
The median of a
random variable R

76
00:04:24,950 --> 00:04:35,300
is the value in the range of
R such that the probability

77
00:04:35,300 --> 00:04:39,700
that the random variable is
less than this median point is

78
00:04:39,700 --> 00:04:42,020
at most 1/2.

79
00:04:42,020 --> 00:04:44,330
And the probability
that random variable

80
00:04:44,330 --> 00:04:48,086
is bigger than the median
is strictly less than 1/2.

81
00:04:48,086 --> 00:04:50,910


82
00:04:50,910 --> 00:04:52,950
Now, some texts
do it differently.

83
00:04:52,950 --> 00:04:56,944
They swap this less than
or equal to with this one.

84
00:04:56,944 --> 00:04:58,610
And it could give you
a different answer

85
00:04:58,610 --> 00:05:01,170
if you do that.

86
00:05:01,170 --> 00:05:04,506
And I think in the text,
actually, we screwed it up.

87
00:05:04,506 --> 00:05:05,880
So we have to get
that corrected.

88
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:07,796
I think we might have
put a less than or equal

89
00:05:07,796 --> 00:05:09,990
here, which is not
the right definition.

90
00:05:09,990 --> 00:05:13,160
So this is the right
definition that we'll use.

91
00:05:13,160 --> 00:05:16,730
So using this definition,
what is the median

92
00:05:16,730 --> 00:05:20,950
of the random variable that
corresponds to rolling a die?

93
00:05:20,950 --> 00:05:24,551
What's the median when I
roll a six sided fair die?

94
00:05:24,551 --> 00:05:27,810


95
00:05:27,810 --> 00:05:32,820
Not 3 and 1/2, because it's
got to be one of the values.

96
00:05:32,820 --> 00:05:35,652
The median does have
to be in the realm

97
00:05:35,652 --> 00:05:36,610
of the random variable.

98
00:05:36,610 --> 00:05:39,340
It has to one of the
attainable values.

99
00:05:39,340 --> 00:05:41,900
What's the median value
when I roll a die?

100
00:05:41,900 --> 00:05:43,280
AUDIENCE: Four.

101
00:05:43,280 --> 00:05:43,980
PROFESSOR: Four.

102
00:05:43,980 --> 00:05:45,580
Let's try that out.

103
00:05:45,580 --> 00:05:49,620
If I plug in 4 here, the
probability I'm less than 4

104
00:05:49,620 --> 00:05:50,790
is 1/2.

105
00:05:50,790 --> 00:05:52,540
Could be 1, 2, or 3.

106
00:05:52,540 --> 00:05:57,330
The probability of greater
than 4 is 5 or six is 1/3.

107
00:05:57,330 --> 00:05:58,470
That's less than 1/2.

108
00:05:58,470 --> 00:06:00,280
So 4 works.

109
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:05,290
3 doesn't work, because the
probability I'm bigger than 3

110
00:06:05,290 --> 00:06:06,710
is 1/2.

111
00:06:06,710 --> 00:06:08,296
So it doesn't work.

112
00:06:08,296 --> 00:06:10,170
And the other definition
sometimes people use

113
00:06:10,170 --> 00:06:11,960
would turn out that
three is the median.

114
00:06:11,960 --> 00:06:14,560


115
00:06:14,560 --> 00:06:16,160
Now, we're not going
to spend any more

116
00:06:16,160 --> 00:06:18,330
time talking about the median.

117
00:06:18,330 --> 00:06:21,430
What's really important in
probability is the mean.

118
00:06:21,430 --> 00:06:23,170
And that's because
you can do a whole lot

119
00:06:23,170 --> 00:06:25,970
more with it in applications.

120
00:06:25,970 --> 00:06:31,770
