00:22:29,430 --> 00:22:33,100
Adam and Martyna were heads,
and it comes out heads.

535
00:22:33,100 --> 00:22:34,870
So Nick is losing here.

536
00:22:34,870 --> 00:22:37,500
The pot is split by
Adam and Martyna.

537
00:22:37,500 --> 00:22:40,540
What does Adam get as a profit?

538
00:22:40,540 --> 00:22:41,040
1.

539
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:43,290
He gets half the part because
he splits with Martyna.

540
00:22:43,290 --> 00:22:49,080
That's $3 he put into,
he gets 1, plus 1.

541
00:22:49,080 --> 00:22:51,710
Now it turns out same
scenario of guesses,

542
00:22:51,710 --> 00:22:54,740
but it comes out tails,
so Nick wins everything.

543
00:22:54,740 --> 00:22:57,550
What's Adam's status here?

544
00:22:57,550 --> 00:22:58,360
Minus 2.

545
00:22:58,360 --> 00:23:01,800
He bet $2, he lost it.

546
00:23:01,800 --> 00:23:07,000
Then we have heads for
Adam, tails for Martyna,

547
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:08,330
heads for Nick.

548
00:23:08,330 --> 00:23:15,550
Coin comes up heads, Adam splits
with Nick, he gets a net of $1.

549
00:23:15,550 --> 00:23:17,300
Same scenario
guesses, but now it's

550
00:23:17,300 --> 00:23:22,770
tails, so Martina wins
everything, Adam loses $2.

551
00:23:22,770 --> 00:23:24,180
Now we go down to
here where it's

552
00:23:24,180 --> 00:23:28,650
heads for Adam, tails
for Martyna and Nick,

553
00:23:28,650 --> 00:23:31,520
and heads comes up, so
Adam wins the whole thing.

554
00:23:31,520 --> 00:23:34,430
What does he get in this case?

555
00:23:34,430 --> 00:23:35,020
Plus 4.

556
00:23:35,020 --> 00:23:36,640
He wins the whole
part of 6 minus 2.

557
00:23:36,640 --> 00:23:38,410
So he gets 4 net.

558
00:23:38,410 --> 00:23:42,690
And then lastly, in this
scenario it comes up tails

559
00:23:42,690 --> 00:23:46,920
and Martina and Nick
split the pot, Adam loses.

560
00:23:46,920 --> 00:23:48,810
Minus 2.

561
00:23:48,810 --> 00:23:52,030
And then the same thing
is happening down here.

562
00:23:52,030 --> 00:23:52,860
Same thing.

563
00:23:52,860 --> 00:23:56,800
It's just everything is
reversed by symmetry.

564
00:23:56,800 --> 00:23:59,290
Now, they're all equally likely.

565
00:23:59,290 --> 00:24:01,380
So what we do to compute
the expected gain

566
00:24:01,380 --> 00:24:05,290
is take each value times its
probability and add them up.

567
00:24:05,290 --> 00:24:08,420
So 0 times 1/16
plus 0 times 1/16

568
00:24:08,420 --> 00:24:12,190
plus 1 times 1/16 minus 2
times 1/16 and so forth.

569
00:24:12,190 --> 00:24:15,450
So it's easier just to add
these up and multiply by 1/16.

570
00:24:15,450 --> 00:24:18,430
And when we do, we get 0.

571
00:24:18,430 --> 00:24:20,070
We get 0.

572
00:24:20,070 --> 00:24:21,510
If I add all these up, I get 0.

573
00:24:21,510 --> 00:24:23,420
The same thing for down here.

574
00:24:23,420 --> 00:24:34,050
So the expected
gain for Adam is 0.

575
00:24:34,050 --> 00:24:35,841
And that is a fair game.

576
00:24:35,841 --> 00:24:39,320


577
00:24:39,320 --> 00:24:40,746
What do you think?

578
00:24:40,746 --> 00:24:42,620
Do you think we'd go to
all that trouble just

579
00:24:42,620 --> 00:24:43,670
to play a fair game?

580
00:24:43,670 --> 00:24:46,800
Or do you think we're trying to
set him up and take his money?

581
00:24:46,800 --> 00:24:48,666
Yeah.

582
00:24:48,666 --> 00:24:51,890
AUDIENCE: Martyna and
Nick are alternating,

583
00:24:51,890 --> 00:24:53,824
so the branch with
the plus 4 goes away.

584
00:24:53,824 --> 00:24:55,240
PROFESSOR: Oh,
that's interesting.

585
00:24:55,240 --> 00:24:56,396
Look what happened here.

586
00:24:56,396 --> 00:24:59,588


587
00:24:59,588 --> 00:25:09,350
Nick and Martina,
well, they're opposite.

588
00:25:09,350 --> 00:25:11,290
That's opposite.

589
00:25:11,290 --> 00:25:12,090
That's opposite.

590
00:25:12,090 --> 00:25:14,180
That's opposite.

591
00:25:14,180 --> 00:25:16,050
You don't suppose they
planned that, do you?

592
00:25:16,050 --> 00:25:19,610


593
00:25:19,610 --> 00:25:22,620
And how could that possibly
help that they just

594
00:25:22,620 --> 00:25:24,414
happened to guess opposite?

595
00:25:24,414 --> 00:25:25,830
AUDIENCE: One of
them always wins.

596
00:25:25,830 --> 00:25:27,920
PROFESSOR: One of
them always wins.

597
00:25:27,920 --> 00:25:29,956
And what does that
mean for poor Adam?

598
00:25:29,956 --> 00:25:31,580
AUDIENCE: He never
takes the whole pot.

599
00:25:31,580 --> 00:25:34,660
PROFESSOR: He never
takes the whole pot.

600
00:25:34,660 --> 00:25:36,430
Well, all right.

601
00:25:36,430 --> 00:25:40,050
Let's see if that
changed anything here.

602
00:25:40,050 --> 00:25:43,950
So if Nick and
Martyna are always

603
00:25:43,950 --> 00:25:48,260
opposite, that means some of
these branches can't occur.

604
00:25:48,260 --> 00:25:51,760
So if Martyna's heads,
Nick is tails, this is out.

605
00:25:51,760 --> 00:25:55,100
So this is happening
with probability 1 now.

606
00:25:55,100 --> 00:26:02,210
So these points are at
1/8 each instead of 1/16.

607
00:26:02,210 --> 00:26:06,770
And these go to 0 because
that branch can't happen.

608
00:26:06,770 --> 00:26:07,490
Same thing here.

609
00:26:07,490 --> 00:26:11,290
When you go tails to
Martyna, Nick can't be tails,

610
00:26:11,290 --> 00:26:13,110
has to be heads.

611
00:26:13,110 --> 00:26:16,590
So these go to 1/8.

612
00:26:16,590 --> 00:26:17,755
These go to 0.

613
00:26:17,755 --> 00:26:21,180


614
00:26:21,180 --> 00:26:24,190
Now, you notice this isn't
working out so well for Adam

615
00:26:24,190 --> 00:26:26,830
because we're putting
more weight here

616
00:26:26,830 --> 00:26:31,750
where he's got a net negative
compared to an even situation.

617
00:26:31,750 --> 00:26:35,200
And here he's gone from a
positive situation, that's

618
00:26:35,200 --> 00:26:37,380
getting wiped out
to a net negative.

619
00:26:37,380 --> 00:26:39,960
So let's compute
his probability now.

620
00:26:39,960 --> 00:26:42,480
And I'll get the same
contribution down here.

621
00:26:42,480 --> 00:26:49,760
I've got 1 minus 2 plus 1
of 0 minus 2 is negative 2.

622
00:26:49,760 --> 00:26:52,760
I'll get a negative 2
down here times 1/8.

623
00:26:52,760 --> 00:26:55,080
In this case, I'll
have the expected gain

624
00:26:55,080 --> 00:27:00,330
for Adam is going to be minus.

625
00:27:00,330 --> 00:27:02,270
Let's make sure I do this right.

626
00:27:02,270 --> 00:27:09,130
It's going to be 2 for the
top and bottom times 1/8

627
00:27:09,130 --> 00:27:12,560
times these guys.

628
00:27:12,560 --> 00:27:17,110
1 minus 2 plus 1 minus 2.

629
00:27:17,110 --> 00:27:20,890
And that equals minus 2.

630
00:27:20,890 --> 00:27:21,880
That's minus 1/2.

631
00:27:21,880 --> 00:27:27,540


632
00:27:27,540 --> 00:27:31,600
So in fact, if they come up
here and guess differently,

633
00:27:31,600 --> 00:27:33,330
who knew?

634
00:27:33,330 --> 00:27:36,610
Now the expected gain
for Adam is minus $0.50.

635
00:27:36,610 --> 00:27:42,420
Every time he plays, he expects
to lose $0.50 on his $2 bet.

636
00:27:42,420 --> 00:27:46,290
That's a lousy game for
Adam to be playing, even

637
00:27:46,290 --> 00:27:50,830
though it seemed very fair.

638
00:27:50,830 --> 00:27:52,680
You see what's going on here?

639
00:27:52,680 --> 00:27:58,790
Now, this kind of trick is used
in all sorts of gambling games.

640
00:27:58,790 --> 00:28:00,790
Maybe you've probably
played some of these games

641
00:28:00,790 --> 00:28:02,623
and may not have realized
maybe somebody was

642
00:28:02,623 --> 00:28:05,240
using this trick against you.

643
00:28:05,240 --> 00:28:06,640
For example, how
many of you have

644
00:28:06,640 --> 00:28:10,424
been in some kind of
sports betting pool?

645
00:28:10,424 --> 00:28:11,840
It's March Madness,
you're betting

646
00:28:11,840 --> 00:28:15,350
on the victors in round one.

647
00:28:15,350 --> 00:28:17,180
It's a football pool
for the weekend.

648
00:28:17,180 --> 00:28:18,550
You're going to guess
against the spread.

649
00:28:18,550 --> 00:28:19,341
Who's going to win?

650
00:28:19,341 --> 00:28:21,420
All right, some of
you have done that.

651
00:28:21,420 --> 00:28:24,160
All right, now everybody
puts $1 into the pool.

652
00:28:24,160 --> 00:28:27,110
And the winner is the
guy who was the most wins

653
00:28:27,110 --> 00:28:28,330
or games picked right.

654
00:28:28,330 --> 00:28:31,240
All the winners split the pot.

655
00:28:31,240 --> 00:28:34,380
Now, what this says, by doing
the same kind of analysis we

656
00:28:34,380 --> 00:28:39,430
just did, is that if you
collude with one or two or three

657
00:28:39,430 --> 00:28:43,260
other players in the pool
to always pick differently

658
00:28:43,260 --> 00:28:47,170
on all the games, it's
going to give you an edge.

659
00:28:47,170 --> 00:28:48,330
Same reasoning.

660
00:28:48,330 --> 00:28:51,280
When they pick differently,
it gives them an edge

661
00:28:51,280 --> 00:28:54,580
and now your expected
return is bigger than 0,

662
00:28:54,580 --> 00:28:57,080
at the expense of
the other players who

663
00:28:57,080 --> 00:28:59,640
just go in and are
putting their picks, if we

664
00:28:59,640 --> 00:29:02,340
assume each one is 50-50.

665
00:29:02,340 --> 00:29:06,590
In fact, a former professor
of statistics here at MIT

666
00:29:06,590 --> 00:29:12,030
used this idea, a guy named
Herman Chernoff, in the 1980s

667
00:29:12,030 --> 00:29:15,190
to beat the state lottery.

668
00:29:15,190 --> 00:29:17,600
Now, everyone knows
that lotteries

669
00:29:17,600 --> 00:29:20,430
are the worst game around
because everybody puts

670
00:29:20,430 --> 00:29:24,080
the money in, the
state takes half,

671
00:29:24,080 --> 00:29:26,850
and then the winners
split the pot.

672
00:29:26,850 --> 00:29:28,540
So it's a horrendous game.

673
00:29:28,540 --> 00:29:31,190
Your expected return is
half of what you put in.

674
00:29:31,190 --> 00:29:33,850
So you expect to lose half your
bet, because the state's taking

675
00:29:33,850 --> 00:29:38,830
half and splitting the remainder
among all the participants.

676
00:29:38,830 --> 00:29:45,170
Now, what Chernoff realized is
that people don't bet randomly.

677
00:29:45,170 --> 00:29:49,540
They tend to pick the
same sets of numbers.

678
00:29:49,540 --> 00:29:50,780
It might be a birthday.

679
00:29:50,780 --> 00:29:54,500
There's only so many
birthdays out there.

680
00:29:54,500 --> 00:29:57,660
Might be number of
home runs Papi's hit,

681
00:29:57,660 --> 00:30:00,530
his batting average,
Pabelbon's ERA.

682
00:30:00,530 --> 00:30:03,100
Who knows?

683
00:30:03,100 --> 00:30:05,880
But they pick a
relatively small set

684
00:30:05,880 --> 00:30:08,620
of numbers that
tend to collapse on.

685
00:30:08,620 --> 00:30:14,370
In fact, if you graph
how people tend to pick.

686
00:30:14,370 --> 00:30:16,010
And say you're
playing pick four,

687
00:30:16,010 --> 00:30:18,187
where you pick four numbers.

688
00:30:18,187 --> 00:30:20,020
And now you look at the
frequency with which

689
00:30:20,020 --> 00:30:21,690
the numbers are picked.

690
00:30:21,690 --> 00:30:25,090
Very crudely it looks
something like this.

691
00:30:25,090 --> 00:30:27,230
Every once in a while
you get a hot ticket

692
00:30:27,230 --> 00:30:31,890
where a lot of people
pick that number.

693
00:30:31,890 --> 00:30:33,940
For example, if you're
picking four numbers,

694
00:30:33,940 --> 00:30:39,422
MIT students might
pick 2, 4, 6, 16.

695
00:30:39,422 --> 00:30:41,380
They might pick that and
so it'd be a big spike

696
00:30:41,380 --> 00:30:43,070
for that set of four.

697
00:30:43,070 --> 00:30:47,274
Down the street they're
probably picking in 1, 2, 3, 4.

698
00:30:47,274 --> 00:30:49,190
Something like that and
there's a spike there.

699
00:30:49,190 --> 00:30:52,280


700
00:30:52,280 --> 00:30:55,550
If you knew this was
the histogram of what

701
00:30:55,550 --> 00:30:58,640
people were picking and
you knew half the pot was

702
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:03,430
going to get split with the
winners, what would you pick?

703
00:31:03,430 --> 00:31:05,215
Would you pick these?

704
00:31:05,215 --> 00:31:07,590
No, because now you're splitting
the pot with 100 people.

705
00:31:07,590 --> 00:31:09,190
That's no good.

706
00:31:09,190 --> 00:31:11,640
You pick down here.

707
00:31:11,640 --> 00:31:15,202
And now when you win,
you get half the pot.

708
00:31:15,202 --> 00:31:17,160
The state always takes
half, but you don't have

709
00:31:17,160 --> 00:31:19,470
to split it with anybody else.

710
00:31:19,470 --> 00:31:21,950
And that means if you're
picking down here,

711
00:31:21,950 --> 00:31:25,820
your expected
return is positive,

712
00:31:25,820 --> 00:31:27,640
even with the state taking half.

713
00:31:27,640 --> 00:31:32,330
Because so much of the money
is piled up in these things.

714
00:31:32,330 --> 00:31:36,910
And so Chernoff proved
that in fact, he

715
00:31:36,910 --> 00:31:39,550
didn't know which
numbers were popular.

716
00:31:39,550 --> 00:31:40,960
He didn't know that.

717
00:31:40,960 --> 00:31:42,009
So what did he do?

718
00:31:42,009 --> 00:31:44,050
If you don't know where
the spikes are but you're

719
00:31:44,050 --> 00:31:46,350
trying to avoid them and
there's not very many spikes,

720
00:31:46,350 --> 00:31:49,470
what would you do to avoid them?

721
00:31:49,470 --> 00:31:51,637
Pick random.

722
00:31:51,637 --> 00:31:53,970
Because if you pick random,
probably you miss the spike.

723
00:31:53,970 --> 00:31:55,680
You're down here.

724
00:31:55,680 --> 00:31:57,680
With a number nobody would
have thought to pick,

725
00:31:57,680 --> 00:31:59,430
if some random number.

726
00:31:59,430 --> 00:32:02,240
And he showed that, in
fact, if you pick randomly,

727
00:32:02,240 --> 00:32:06,870
your expected gain for
the lottery at the time

728
00:32:06,870 --> 00:32:10,500
was 7%, or $0.7 on the dollar.

729
00:32:10,500 --> 00:32:13,500
So positive even with
the state taking half.

730
00:32:13,500 --> 00:32:17,160
Now, shortly after that,
you saw the proliferation

731
00:32:17,160 --> 00:32:20,970
of these random machines that
we create random numbers.

732
00:32:20,970 --> 00:32:23,090
Because the state wanted
to balance it out and not

733
00:32:23,090 --> 00:32:25,310
have this kind of a scenario.

734
00:32:25,310 --> 00:32:26,910
So now a lot of the
picks are randomly

735
00:32:26,910 --> 00:32:29,570
generated in a lot
of the lotteries.

736
00:32:29,570 --> 00:32:34,210


737
00:32:34,210 --> 00:32:36,280
These things are not
immediately obvious,

738
00:32:36,280 --> 00:32:42,240
but become very clear once you
know the mathematics behind it.

739
00:32:42,240 --> 00:32:43,860
Any questions?

740
00:32:43,860 --> 00:32:44,645
Yeah.

741
00:32:44,645 --> 00:32:47,900
AUDIENCE: How would a
person hit a random number?

742
00:32:47,900 --> 00:32:49,870
PROFESSOR: Oh, you go to
your favorite computer

743
00:32:49,870 --> 00:32:52,290
and do a random
number generator.

744
00:32:52,290 --> 00:32:54,490
Now, that's not
perfectly random.

745
00:32:54,490 --> 00:32:56,050
People do get into
a science of this

746
00:32:56,050 --> 00:32:58,512
where they're
certain cosmic rays

747
00:32:58,512 --> 00:33:00,470
or whatever hitting the
earth and the frequency

748
00:33:00,470 --> 00:33:02,136
they try to get random
numbers out of it

749
00:33:02,136 --> 00:33:04,220
or certain kinds
of clocks and stuff

750
00:33:04,220 --> 00:33:07,090
like that, the tiny
low order bits.

751
00:33:07,090 --> 00:33:10,069
Actually getting really
independent random numbers

752
00:33:10,069 --> 00:33:10,860
can be challenging.

753
00:33:10,860 --> 00:33:13,140
A lot of the things you do
with a computer generating

754
00:33:13,140 --> 00:33:16,140
random numbers, they're
distributed nicely,

755
00:33:16,140 --> 00:33:17,850
but they're not
mutually independent.

756
00:33:17,850 --> 00:33:20,250
And there's whole texts
that go into how to do

757
00:33:20,250 --> 00:33:22,385
that for mutual independence.

758
00:33:22,385 --> 00:33:24,260
Getting something that's
fair for one of them

759
00:33:24,260 --> 00:33:27,100
is not too hard.

760
00:33:27,100 --> 00:33:30,920
Any questions about that?

761
00:33:30,920 --> 00:33:32,970
There's another example.

762
00:33:32,970 --> 00:33:34,920
How many people
ever participated

763
00:33:34,920 --> 00:33:38,090
in a Super Bowl bet?

764
00:33:38,090 --> 00:33:40,810
OK, like maybe you're trying to
guess the over under on point

765
00:33:40,810 --> 00:33:42,930
scored.

766
00:33:42,930 --> 00:33:47,050
And the person who guesses close
to the total number of points

767
00:33:47,050 --> 00:33:48,370
wins the pot.

768
00:33:48,370 --> 00:33:50,760
And if there's a
tie, it's shared.

769
00:33:50,760 --> 00:33:53,490
So in that kind of
situation, some people

770
00:33:53,490 --> 00:33:56,570
figured out that the average
number of points scored

771
00:33:56,570 --> 00:34:00,860
in a Super Bowl is, say, 30.

772
00:34:00,860 --> 00:34:07,730
And a lot of the guesses then
will cluster around 30 points.

773
00:34:07,730 --> 00:34:10,840
Now, if you knew this and you
knew a lot of the guesses,

774
00:34:10,840 --> 00:34:13,639
because there may be people who
cared betting, where would you

775
00:34:13,639 --> 00:34:16,560
make, say, this is, I don't
know, 40 and this is 20,

776
00:34:16,560 --> 00:34:19,440
where would you guess?

777
00:34:19,440 --> 00:34:20,480
You could guess here.

778
00:34:20,480 --> 00:34:22,120
That's a good one.

779
00:34:22,120 --> 00:34:24,620
Or you could guess here.

780
00:34:24,620 --> 00:34:27,448
Not only are you not going to
share the pot, which helps you,

781
00:34:27,448 --> 00:34:29,739
but in this case you'd
actually, because being closest,

782
00:34:29,739 --> 00:34:32,630
you'd capture all
the scores out here.

783
00:34:32,630 --> 00:34:34,870
So that's really good.

784
00:34:34,870 --> 00:34:38,198
So these are the best guesses to
make for your expected return,

785
00:34:38,198 --> 00:34:40,489
