p is 1 over 1 minus 1 minus p.

1044
00:50:32,702 --> 00:50:33,660
And that's very simple.

1045
00:50:33,660 --> 00:50:37,300
That's 1 over p.

1046
00:50:37,300 --> 00:50:40,310
So the expected time to
fail, the expected step

1047
00:50:40,310 --> 00:50:43,210
of when you're going to
fail, is 1 over p where

1048
00:50:43,210 --> 00:50:45,500
p is the failure probability.

1049
00:50:45,500 --> 00:50:50,120
So for example, if you have a 1%
chance of failing on any step,

1050
00:50:50,120 --> 00:50:54,510
your mean time to
failure is what?

1051
00:50:54,510 --> 00:50:55,322
100.

1052
00:50:55,322 --> 00:50:57,260
1 over 0.01.

1053
00:50:57,260 --> 00:51:01,870
So very easy to compute
mean time to failure.

1054
00:51:01,870 --> 00:51:06,264
Any questions about that?

1055
00:51:06,264 --> 00:51:08,430
Of course, you can do it
with the other definitions,

1056
00:51:08,430 --> 00:51:11,660
but the calculations are
a little more painful.

1057
00:51:11,660 --> 00:51:12,573
Yeah.

1058
00:51:12,573 --> 00:51:13,906
AUDIENCE: Why are we summing it?

1059
00:51:13,906 --> 00:51:17,250
Is it like an accumulative
solution basically?

1060
00:51:17,250 --> 00:51:18,860
PROFESSOR: Why are we summing?

1061
00:51:18,860 --> 00:51:20,830
Well, that's the definition.

1062
00:51:20,830 --> 00:51:25,930
The theorem says the expected
value of a random variable

1063
00:51:25,930 --> 00:51:30,832
is the sum of the probability
that it's bigger than i.

1064
00:51:30,832 --> 00:51:32,040
That's what the theorem says.

1065
00:51:32,040 --> 00:51:34,540
So we're just plugging
into the theorem.

1066
00:51:34,540 --> 00:51:37,420
And then the theorem
was proved based

1067
00:51:37,420 --> 00:51:42,020
on the corollary, which came
from the theorem and then

1068
00:51:42,020 --> 00:51:43,129
the definition.

1069
00:51:43,129 --> 00:51:44,670
So we went through
a series of steps.

1070
00:51:44,670 --> 00:51:47,510
We started with a definition
of expected value, which

1071
00:51:47,510 --> 00:51:48,599
makes sense.

1072
00:51:48,599 --> 00:51:50,140
Then we got another
way to compute it

1073
00:51:50,140 --> 00:51:51,181
based on that definition.

1074
00:51:51,181 --> 00:51:53,770


1075
00:51:53,770 --> 00:51:56,782
And then a corollary
to that and then

1076
00:51:56,782 --> 00:51:58,490
we use the corollary
to prove another way

1077
00:51:58,490 --> 00:51:59,710
of computing expected values.

1078
00:51:59,710 --> 00:52:01,754
We went through a
bunch of general steps

1079
00:52:01,754 --> 00:52:03,670
and then we used, basically
you could use this

1080
00:52:03,670 --> 00:52:06,354
as a definition of this
point for expected value.

1081
00:52:06,354 --> 00:52:08,020
And it just says you
sum those things up

1082
00:52:08,020 --> 00:52:08,978
and you get the answer.

1083
00:52:08,978 --> 00:52:12,510


1084
00:52:12,510 --> 00:52:13,568
Any other questions?

1085
00:52:13,568 --> 00:52:16,990


1086
00:52:16,990 --> 00:52:19,380
OK, there's a variation
on this problem

1087
00:52:19,380 --> 00:52:22,890
that you see all the time
in sort of trick questions

1088
00:52:22,890 --> 00:52:25,650
or in the popular
press sometime, that

1089
00:52:25,650 --> 00:52:27,220
often confuses people.

1090
00:52:27,220 --> 00:52:29,630
People sometimes think
of it as a paradox,

1091
00:52:29,630 --> 00:52:31,930
though it's not really one.

1092
00:52:31,930 --> 00:52:34,060
And the example's something
like the following.

1093
00:52:34,060 --> 00:52:36,610
Say that a couple, they're
going to have kids.

1094
00:52:36,610 --> 00:52:38,890
What they really
want is a baby girl.

1095
00:52:38,890 --> 00:52:40,390
They get a boy,
fine, but that's not

1096
00:52:40,390 --> 00:52:41,598
what they're concerned about.

1097
00:52:41,598 --> 00:52:43,440
They want to have a baby girl.

1098
00:52:43,440 --> 00:52:45,310
And let's say that
each time they have

1099
00:52:45,310 --> 00:52:48,300
a kid it's 50-50 boy or girl.

1100
00:52:48,300 --> 00:52:51,710
And let's say that it's
mutually independent from one

1101
00:52:51,710 --> 00:52:54,380
kid to the next, which
is not true in practice.

1102
00:52:54,380 --> 00:52:55,735
There tends to be correlation.

1103
00:52:55,735 --> 00:52:57,860
But let's assume it's
mutually independent from one

1104
00:52:57,860 --> 00:52:59,500
kid to the next.

1105
00:52:59,500 --> 00:53:03,750
Now, if on the first
try a couple get a girl,

1106
00:53:03,750 --> 00:53:06,110
great, they're done, they
have one kid, that's it,

1107
00:53:06,110 --> 00:53:07,680
because they just wanted a girl.

1108
00:53:07,680 --> 00:53:11,140
If they get a boy,
OK, try again.

1109
00:53:11,140 --> 00:53:14,890
And they keep trying again
until they get the girl,

1110
00:53:14,890 --> 00:53:16,480
even if it's 50 kids.

1111
00:53:16,480 --> 00:53:18,570
They wait till
they get the girl.

1112
00:53:18,570 --> 00:53:21,830
And the question is,
how many baby boys

1113
00:53:21,830 --> 00:53:27,190
do you expect to get
before you have the girl?

1114
00:53:27,190 --> 00:53:27,690
what's?

1115
00:53:27,690 --> 00:53:32,461
The expected number of boys to
get the girl, then you quit?

1116
00:53:32,461 --> 00:53:37,331
So let's do that.

1117
00:53:37,331 --> 00:53:48,070


1118
00:53:48,070 --> 00:53:49,735
So we want to know.

1119
00:53:49,735 --> 00:53:52,690
We have the following data.

1120
00:53:52,690 --> 00:53:57,860
The probability of a boy is 1/2.

1121
00:53:57,860 --> 00:54:00,838
You keep having boys until
you get a girl, then you quit.

1122
00:54:00,838 --> 00:54:06,840


1123
00:54:06,840 --> 00:54:10,527
We're going to let R
be the random variable

1124
00:54:10,527 --> 00:54:11,485
for the number of boys.

1125
00:54:11,485 --> 00:54:14,050


1126
00:54:14,050 --> 00:54:21,290
And everything is mutually
independent from one child

1127
00:54:21,290 --> 00:54:23,300
to the next.

1128
00:54:23,300 --> 00:54:28,430
How many people think you expect
to have more boys than the one

1129
00:54:28,430 --> 00:54:30,330
girl?

1130
00:54:30,330 --> 00:54:32,680
You keep having boys
till you get the girl.

1131
00:54:32,680 --> 00:54:33,880
Most people think this.

1132
00:54:33,880 --> 00:54:39,390
How many people think you expect
to have fewer than one boy?

1133
00:54:39,390 --> 00:54:40,630
Nobody.

1134
00:54:40,630 --> 00:54:43,136
How many people think you
expect to have an equal number?

1135
00:54:43,136 --> 00:54:44,160
Expect one boy.

1136
00:54:44,160 --> 00:54:46,140
Good, OK, so that's the answer.

1137
00:54:46,140 --> 00:54:48,700
In fact, you expect
to have just one boy.

1138
00:54:48,700 --> 00:54:52,859
And the proof, we sort
of just did it here.

1139
00:54:52,859 --> 00:54:54,650
Now, in this case,
we're going to set it up

1140
00:54:54,650 --> 00:54:56,460
as a mean time to failure.

1141
00:54:56,460 --> 00:54:58,480
Same kind of thing.

1142
00:54:58,480 --> 00:55:01,950
Now, in this case the failure
mode, they want the girl,

1143
00:55:01,950 --> 00:55:05,640
but that's when you stop,
so that's the failure mode.

1144
00:55:05,640 --> 00:55:07,210
And a working step
is you have a boy

1145
00:55:07,210 --> 00:55:08,860
and you keep having the
working steps until you have

1146
00:55:08,860 --> 00:55:10,570
failure mode and then you stop.

1147
00:55:10,570 --> 00:55:12,630
And in this case,
we're not counting

1148
00:55:12,630 --> 00:55:13,610
the step when you stop.

1149
00:55:13,610 --> 00:55:19,270
So we know from that that
the expected value of R

1150
00:55:19,270 --> 00:55:22,620
is 1 over p, which
is going to be 1/2.

1151
00:55:22,620 --> 00:55:26,420
That's the number of
children you have.

1152
00:55:26,420 --> 00:55:30,170
And that equals the
mean time to failure.

1153
00:55:30,170 --> 00:55:34,250
Minus the girl.

1154
00:55:34,250 --> 00:55:37,810
Because you count the girl
as one of the children.

1155
00:55:37,810 --> 00:55:40,039
And that's going to be the
expected number of boys.

1156
00:55:40,039 --> 00:55:41,580
So number of children
you're expected

1157
00:55:41,580 --> 00:55:43,880
to have minus the girl.

1158
00:55:43,880 --> 00:55:44,770
This is 1 over 1/2.

1159
00:55:44,770 --> 00:55:49,115


1160
00:55:49,115 --> 00:55:53,330
And that is 2 minus 1 equals 1.

1161
00:55:53,330 --> 00:55:58,770
So you expect to have one
boy before you get the girl.

1162
00:55:58,770 --> 00:56:02,930
Any questions on that?

1163
00:56:02,930 --> 00:56:06,180
OK, how about this?

1164
00:56:06,180 --> 00:56:09,840
Some couples want to have
at least one of each sex.

1165
00:56:09,840 --> 00:56:13,530
They want to have at least
one boy and one girl.

1166
00:56:13,530 --> 00:56:16,170
So they keep having children
until they get one of each

1167
00:56:16,170 --> 00:56:18,170
and then they stop.

1168
00:56:18,170 --> 00:56:20,210
How many children do
they expect to have?

1169
00:56:20,210 --> 00:56:25,910


1170
00:56:25,910 --> 00:56:27,580
Somebody said two.

1171
00:56:27,580 --> 00:56:30,820
That's a minimum number.

1172
00:56:30,820 --> 00:56:34,380
So it's not likely to
be the expected number.

1173
00:56:34,380 --> 00:56:35,580
Three.

1174
00:56:35,580 --> 00:56:37,730
Well, OK, who said three?

1175
00:56:37,730 --> 00:56:39,030
Why do you think three?

1176
00:56:39,030 --> 00:56:42,848
AUDIENCE: Because you have to
have at least the first two,

1177
00:56:42,848 --> 00:56:45,820
so it can be greater than one.

1178
00:56:45,820 --> 00:56:48,302
I mean, one probability
is greater than one child,

1179
00:56:48,302 --> 00:56:50,534
one probability is
greater than two children.

1180
00:56:50,534 --> 00:56:55,080
And after that it's halves
which add up to one.

1181
00:56:55,080 --> 00:56:56,330
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's right.

1182
00:56:56,330 --> 00:56:57,163
That's a good proof.

1183
00:56:57,163 --> 00:56:58,000
Very good.

1184
00:56:58,000 --> 00:56:58,850
That'll work.

1185
00:56:58,850 --> 00:56:59,838
Yeah, yeah.

1186
00:56:59,838 --> 00:57:01,421
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about what

1187
00:57:01,421 --> 00:57:02,383
you were doing before.

1188
00:57:02,383 --> 00:57:05,429
If you were to switch your
expectations for a girl

1189
00:57:05,429 --> 00:57:07,674
and boy, wouldn't it come
out to the same number

1190
00:57:07,674 --> 00:57:10,570
but wouldn't it kind
of contradict itself?

1191
00:57:10,570 --> 00:57:12,940
PROFESSOR: No, if you stopped
as soon as you had a boy,

1192
00:57:12,940 --> 00:57:15,780
you'd expect to have one
girl before you got a boy.

1193
00:57:15,780 --> 00:57:17,057
Totally symmetric.

1194
00:57:17,057 --> 00:57:19,140
In this case, we're stopping
when we get the girl,

1195
00:57:19,140 --> 00:57:21,560
so we expect to have one boy.

1196
00:57:21,560 --> 00:57:24,354
You might have none, you might
have one, you might have two.

1197
00:57:24,354 --> 00:57:26,770
and as he mentions, if you put
the probabilities in there,

1198
00:57:26,770 --> 00:57:28,000
they will work
out the right way,

1199
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:30,291
but we just did it simpler
by the mean time to failure.

1200
00:57:30,291 --> 00:57:32,840


1201
00:57:32,840 --> 00:57:34,910
And in fact, there's
also another proof,

1202
00:57:34,910 --> 00:57:37,220
what you're doing.

1203
00:57:37,220 --> 00:57:39,530
Another way to think
about how many kids

1204
00:57:39,530 --> 00:57:41,400
you have to get one of each.

1205
00:57:41,400 --> 00:57:43,880
Well you have the first kid.

1206
00:57:43,880 --> 00:57:47,260
And now you have this
problem, because you

1207
00:57:47,260 --> 00:57:49,200
want one of the other sex.

1208
00:57:49,200 --> 00:57:51,980
And you keep on trying to
get one of the other sex

1209
00:57:51,980 --> 00:57:55,850
and you expect to
have two children

1210
00:57:55,850 --> 00:57:57,090
to get one of the other sex.

1211
00:57:57,090 --> 00:57:58,420
So you have one to start.

1212
00:57:58,420 --> 00:57:59,760
Whatever it is doesn't matter.

1213
00:57:59,760 --> 00:58:01,690
And now you expect
to have two more

1214
00:58:01,690 --> 00:58:03,280
until you hit the other sex.

1215
00:58:03,280 --> 00:58:05,970
So a total of three is the
expected number of children

1216
00:58:05,970 --> 00:58:10,985
to get one boy and
one girl, at least.

1217
00:58:10,985 --> 00:58:13,314
Any questions about expectation?

1218
00:58:13,314 --> 00:58:15,980


1219
00:58:15,980 --> 00:58:22,010
OK, let's do another example.

1220
00:58:22,010 --> 00:58:26,120
This comes up all the
time in experimental work.

1221
00:58:26,120 --> 00:58:29,540
Probably all of you are going to
have some example at some point

1222
00:58:29,540 --> 00:58:33,050
where you're going to
do a problem like this.

1223
00:58:33,050 --> 00:58:37,020
And most all the time,
people do it wrong.

1224
00:58:37,020 --> 00:58:39,520
So let's see an example.

1225
00:58:39,520 --> 00:58:44,390
Say that you want to measure the
latency of some communications

1226
00:58:44,390 --> 00:58:46,410
channel.

1227
00:58:46,410 --> 00:58:49,490
And you want to know
what's the average latency.

1228
00:58:49,490 --> 00:58:52,570
So you set up an experiment.

1229
00:58:52,570 --> 00:58:54,180
You send a package
to the channel,

1230
00:58:54,180 --> 00:58:56,740
you measure when it started,
when it got to the other end,

1231
00:58:56,740 --> 00:59:00,900
and you record the answer,
and then you do it 100 times

1232
00:59:00,900 --> 00:59:02,940
and you take the average.

1233
00:59:02,940 --> 00:59:06,270
And you say that's the expected
latency of the channel.

1234
00:59:06,270 --> 00:59:10,827
Very, very typical kind of thing
to do, and sometimes OK to do.

1235
00:59:10,827 --> 00:59:12,160
So you'd do something like this.

1236
00:59:12,160 --> 00:59:15,690
You pick a random
variable D, which

1237
00:59:15,690 --> 00:59:23,197
is going to denote the
delay of a packet going

1238
00:59:23,197 --> 00:59:24,030
through the channel.

1239
00:59:24,030 --> 00:59:28,560


1240
00:59:28,560 --> 00:59:31,010
And there's, of course,
some underlying distribution

1241
00:59:31,010 --> 00:59:35,990
here, which we'll
denote by f of x.

1242
00:59:35,990 --> 00:59:38,500
And that's just the
probability that D equals x.

1243
00:59:38,500 --> 00:59:40,510
That's the probability
distribution function.

1244
00:59:40,510 --> 00:59:46,450


1245
00:59:46,450 --> 00:59:49,120
And as part of doing
your stuff, you

1246
00:59:49,120 --> 00:59:52,110
notice that if I
look at plot f here,

1247
00:59:52,110 --> 00:59:58,320
if I look at x on that
axis and f of x here,

1248
00:59:58,320 --> 01:00:00,045
it looks something like this.

1249
01:00:00,045 --> 01:00:02,910


1250
01:00:02,910 --> 01:00:05,100
The chance of
getting the observed

1251
01:00:05,100 --> 01:00:09,290
cases where I got a long delay
were small, low probability.

1252
01:00:09,290 --> 01:00:11,890
And almost all the time
I got a short delay.

1253
01:00:11,890 --> 01:00:14,540
So very typically you'll get
a curve that looks something

1254
01:00:14,540 --> 01:00:17,430
like that in terms
of the observations

1255
01:00:17,430 --> 01:00:20,600
of your experiment.

1256
01:00:20,600 --> 01:00:25,930
And say that you do your
experiment 100 times

1257
01:00:25,930 --> 01:00:28,710
and the average latency
was 10 milliseconds.

1258
01:00:28,710 --> 01:00:31,887


1259
01:00:31,887 --> 01:00:33,720
And sometimes you want
to be really careful,

1260
01:00:33,720 --> 01:00:37,150
so you do the whole thing
again, you do another 100 times.

1261
01:00:37,150 --> 01:00:39,190
And maybe it's nine
milliseconds the next time.

1262
01:00:39,190 --> 01:00:41,280
And that sort of
confirms your belief

1263
01:00:41,280 --> 01:00:43,250
that your first
experiment was valid

1264
01:00:43,250 --> 01:00:45,430
and that the expected
latency on this channel

1265
01:00:45,430 --> 01:00:48,510
is 10 milliseconds.

1266
01:00:48,510 --> 01:00:51,390
Sounds pretty good.

1267
01:00:51,390 --> 01:00:53,710
But it can be completely wrong.

1268
01:00:53,710 --> 01:00:55,390
And not just because
you're unlucky,

1269
01:00:55,390 --> 01:00:57,870
but because you're taking
a simple method like that.

1270
01:00:57,870 --> 01:01:04,400
And let me show you an
example where it is way off.

1271
01:01:04,400 --> 01:01:14,310


1272
01:01:14,310 --> 01:01:17,210
All right, say you
were just a little more

1273
01:01:17,210 --> 01:01:19,350
sophisticated about this.

1274
01:01:19,350 --> 01:01:22,010
And when you did
your observations,

1275
01:01:22,010 --> 01:01:26,930
you tried to figure out what
this curve really looks like.

1276
01:01:26,930 --> 01:01:29,090
And say that you,
looking at the data,

1277
01:01:29,090 --> 01:01:33,330
concluded that the probability
that you have a delay of more

1278
01:01:33,330 --> 01:01:37,610
than i milliseconds is 1 and i.

1279
01:01:37,610 --> 01:01:41,480
That looks like this curve,
as close as anything.

1280
01:01:41,480 --> 01:01:45,234
So from your data,
you conclude this.

1281
01:01:45,234 --> 01:01:47,150
That's a little more
sophisticated conclusion,

1282
01:01:47,150 --> 01:01:49,300
because now you've
identified what

1283
01:01:49,300 --> 01:01:51,560
you believe the
distribution is, which

1284
01:01:51,560 --> 01:01:55,000
is stronger than expectation.

1285
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:58,754
How would you go about
figuring out the expected value

1286
01:01:58,754 --> 01:01:59,920
if you had that information?

1287
01:01:59,920 --> 01:02:03,800


1288
01:02:03,800 --> 01:02:06,380
I mean, you could average
the 100 sample points.

1289
01:02:06,380 --> 01:02:10,550
But is there any way, if you
assume this, what would you

1290
01:02:10,550 --> 01:02:14,680
do for the expected value?

1291
01:02:14,680 --> 01:02:16,500
Yeah, did I erase the theorem?

1292
01:02:16,500 --> 01:02:18,870
No, it's over there.

1293
01:02:18,870 --> 01:02:22,190
We just plug it to the theorem.

1294
01:02:22,190 --> 01:02:23,590
The expected delay
is going to be

1295
01:02:23,590 --> 01:02:29,800
the sum of those probabilities
from 1 to infinity.

